segments.text: It's a lot of small things that finally add up to make any difference.
For example, I used to teach in OCS and also up in the military academy.
For example, you go to a mess hall and you see where the lines stand.
Usually they're waiting to go in.
It's open because they're hungry.
And you look around and you see cigarette butts all over the ground.
One would conclude, now this is probably a
undisciplined unit.
No, that's not it.
You can take that same unit without beating them over the head and put butt cans along the way.
And you'll find that that same unit would use those butt cans because they know they themselves have to go around and pick up the cigarette.
So most of the deficiencies and decrepancies in the unit is because the leader, supposed to be a leader, doesn't anticipate and doesn't think
and doesn't support his men, doesn't make life easier for them.
If you do that, they feel obligated to do something for you.
And if you never get them to where they feel obligated, you know, cooperate and not let you down, not let the fellow men down appear or disappear.
Now, we're talking about this right now, and I'd like to get on this topic, and that is leadership.
In a sense, now, you're defining leadership for me.
Is that right?
Well, I'm describing it.
You're talking about anticipation.
Would you define it for me?
Well, of course, simplicity of leadership is influencing others.
And what values do you think that a leader should have?
What values?
What values?
You've already mentioned high moral values.
And integrity, you mentioned that, too.
Well, of course, I'm not going to tick off all of the qualities of the leader, you know, which integrity, and all the other things, and loyalty.
Loyal also, by the way, is to your superiors as well as even more so to your subordinates.
Now we get into an area, and this is very interesting,
When are you a chronic or consistent yes guy?
Or do you have the courage or your conviction to disagree?
Of course, now we're describing judgment.
You're being disloyal if you know full well that whatever he said or plans to do is wrong.
If you let him go ahead and do it.
So then in the case of a judgment, you've got to go in and maybe by yourself close the door and say this is what the situation is.
You're making a big mistake.
And it's just not my opinion, because I know what the situation is.
And if he said, and you listened to him, and he said, well, I considered all of that.
But I know what I'm doing.
You could even go so far as to say, would you mind if we go together to the next station line and discuss this?
Because I don't want to put you on the spot.
And many of them will say, yeah, come on, let's go.
It all depends on the rapport you have, and you have to cultivate that.
You just don't all at once go in and disagree with somebody.
Now, you're not brown-nosing at all to do that.
That's the way to do business.
I do that to anybody.
I do that to my friend.
But many people won't do that.
First, they start picking a fight with a superior headquarters.
Maybe they haven't got the guts to pick it with a commanding officer, but they'll pick it with a staff because he outranks them and gives them a hard time.
In other words, you just develop an environment that is not very healthy.
So we could go on and on on many things about accomplishing an objective, particularly in a military unit.
And you have to constantly work at it.
You never get to the unit, you know, well, I've got it where I want it now, and I can relax.
You're always trying to improve while harassing.
Now, I went out with a commanding officer of mine, I'm not going to mention it, at Christmas time.
The way that I had already been trained, the time that you go around and inspect the mess and buck them up and discipline them,
It's not on Christmas Day or Thanksgiving Day, but it's either before or some other time.
Because those guys get up real early, you know, and they've been working and they've got to decorate the dining hall.
Well, I was so embarrassed because I went around with a commanding officer, and I was with him.
I found an excuse if I'd known that.
It was on Christmas morning.
He went in there and he started raising hell, first because somebody was delayed in calling attention, and
Then he didn't like the way the tables decorated.
He checked out the kitchen.
And he didn't like what he saw there.
He didn't like the way they was cooking.
And he proceeded to line them all up and really chew them out.
And as we walked out, I looked back around at them, and they were astounded, amazing.
Kind of looked at each other, what in the world happened here.
They were very proud of everything that they were doing.
Now, he had an artillery background, so I'll say the infantry just, they suffer together, and they have a little bit more compassion.
Now, I would do the same thing that he did, but I would have done it either the day before or the day after, but mainly before, so that you know what to expect.
Now, a battle group commander or battalion commander, they're closer to the troops.
He may not hit that mess for another year or maybe even more than that, since he's got many men.
So he doesn't really build the morale of that.
He doesn't discipline that unit.
They just feel frustrated, and this is a hell of a way to do it.
And they'll think about it the rest of the day.
You fall there a day, and it's Christmas.
They should be complimented for having gotten up early and everything they're doing.
Do you think that people in the military get ahead the same way as people in professional or business life?
I think it's a great similarity, though, in many cases.
What are the differences?
Now you're almost talking about this book, What Makes Sammy Run.
Did you ever read that book years ago about this guy who
who studied every situation and can exploit it and exploit people and go to the top.
I think it probably happens.
There are a lot of similarities, but the objectives are a little bit different, because one is personal gain, and that may occur in the military in most of the cases.
But to a lesser extent, are you saying?
Yeah.
The thing that many people don't understand, civilians I'm talking about,
is that the only objective of having a military establishment is to win in case we have war, to save lives and have the equipment, so forth.
We're faced with that.
Of course, the other mission, the main mission, is to, that I certainly believe in, and most people, that arms secure peace, that strength
will deter war.
Weakness will invite war.
So you have to be strong in peacetime.
You can't wait, like we did in Korea, until we get involved in the fight and play catch up.
Or like we really did in Vietnam, the same way, although we had the ability.
So you work longer hours.
You make more sacrifices.
The family makes the sacrifices, just like your wife is sacrificing.
That's because you're gone all the time.
And she's working.
That's one thing.
But they have to raise the children, hardship, get their furniture lost, broken.
In other words, that's really rough.
So in other words, you have to sacrifice more climbing in the military leadership positions than you do in the business, you think?
I don't think I would describe my advancement as climbing.
I think you do things like you think they should be done.
And that will follow.

I never in my mind ever said, now I think, now I won't contradict myself, I wanted to go to the Army War College because that would be climbing, that would be advancement, I know that's what you had in mind, that's climbing.
But I never considered if I did this, then I would look good to the superior and I would win brownie points.
Now in the Army right now,
In fact, there was a book written about this, and the Army has been reacting to that book for quite some time.
That is that we have ruined the Army office structure because we put such emphasis on gaining brownie points that we don't look at our unit like I just described.
We only do the things that we will look good and to hell with the other guy.
Of course, we would like to look like we didn't do it that way
But we're only interested in our own personal advancement.
And we're only looking for the jobs that will help us.
Well, do you think there's any validity?
Well, it all depends on the individual.
Oh, it depends on the individual.
Yeah.
Well, would you have considered yourself ambitious?
Yeah.
Because I wanted to excel.
I wanted as far as I can remember.
even in a selfish way.
I wanted to excel in school, but I didn't want to study because I wanted to do the other things.
As a result, I was just an average student.
I wanted to excel in athletics.
I was going to graduate from college.
I didn't know how, but I was going to do it some way.
I mean, by working and not by cheating, of course.
And what about in the military?
Were you ambitious?
You just said that you never thought about becoming a general, yet at the same time,
You wanted to excel, were you ambitious?
I wanted to excel, I wanted to be...
I wanted to make, I would call that ambitious, because I wanted, but I wasn't going to, I didn't ever attempt to walk over the bodies of somebody else to get there.

In other words, I never tried to enhance my, or reflect favorably on somebody at the expense of making somebody else, even if it's a half-truth, you know, like, anything went wrong, it's his fault, and...
Even though he's claiming credit, I'm the one behind all this.
And some do that.
And I'm sure they do that in civilian life.
Oh, sure.
Okay.

There's another issue along these lines that I'd like to have you comment on, and that is that some people maintain that there's a military mind, that the military does things a certain way, which is different than the civilians.
Do you think that there's a military mind?
You ask me all sorts of questions that are not simple to answer.
No, they're not simple at all.
To a civilian, there's a military mind, especially a civilian that's never had any experience in the military.
Now, I'm sure your attitude towards a military mind would be different than somebody who's never had any, because you know what discipline is.
If you've been aboard ship, everybody's got to pull this
job to make it run.
And they've done a tremendous job.
Look at all these years we've operated nuclear submarines and carriers with only minor accidents.
They think they're minor.
But you have to do it right.
Look what happened on this carrier here recently when they had this terrible accident with this Aggie, you know, which wasn't his fault.
I mean, he wasn't on drugs or anything.
He just
didn't hit the carrier.
So experience then, I think, influence whether or not there's a military mind.
Now, I say it's a military mind.
What is the military mind?
Would you define it?
Well, I think it's a disciplined individual who likes to see things done according to a plan.
And he makes a plan.
Because he doesn't want to get caught short.
He's always thinking ahead.
Now it's probably called a scenario of what might happen.
What if, in other words.
What if this?
What if that?
And he has mentally made a plan in that situation.
So he tries not to ever be surprised, whether it's running down the highway or whether it's in military subjects or whatever it is.
or go into a movie or play.
Mimi gets mad at me because she says I'm a pessimist because I'm always thinking of the things that might happen.
She says, why don't you pause to be an optimist?
This is a thing that could happen, and I'm just thinking about now if it would happen, what would I do?
What could we do?
Was it getting a flat on the road or whatever it is?
I'm thinking about it.
Getting gasoline or running out of gasoline.
So they planned.
if he's got a good one.
We've already talked about patriotism.
He's actually an individual, or you could say he's selfless, because he will put principle above himself.
You hope that he's an honorable individual, just like at the military academy and elsewhere, where you have duty, honor, and country, that he won't lie still so that
When he says something, you can take it as being factual, the truth.
So you add those and a lot of other things, and I don't have time to think about none.
And you see his style of life.
He even attempts to be neat.
That is, keep his hair relatively cut.
I mean, according to the styles, it's different today.
It's close to breath.
He tried.
He wears neat clothes and so forth.
He mowed his yard.
I even mowed the vacant lot before they built this house over there.
I had a civilian friend up the street.
I'm sure he said, because of military money, he said, I see you out there mowing that vacant lot.
That's not your lot.
Why are you doing that?
I said, because I can't stand those weeds.
You know, I can't stand it.
Right up to my line.
He thought it was stupid, and he's right.
You know, it only improves.
But I couldn't have a military mine.
They asked me why.
You wanted to see it neat.
Yeah.
They said, why?
You sure do keep your jasmine out here.
I trim it all the time, you know, and keep the leaves trimmed out.
And I have people stop and say, you've got the neatest looking place ever.
I could have said, well, it's called a military mine.
I just can't stand to see things that's not orderly.
And I think that's part of all these years of training, see.
Yeah.
I can't stand to see clothes on the floor hanging.
I hate to see people that have no sense of value as far as money and things like that go.
Now, I'm sure others may view me as being queer.
So they could call that a military mind.
Also, military people don't make good presidents.
Eisenhower didn't.
Main reason, because he was a guy.
First, you know, we had the U-2 flight.
And they said, now, Mr. President, that's a CIA flight.
There is no reason at all for you to accept responsibility.
You go ahead and tell the world that this was, a country did this, and I apologize for it.
But he didn't.
He said, absolutely not.
I'm personally taking the responsibility.
In other words, he didn't try to cover up or evade anything.
And there are a lot of other things that occurred during his administration that he did it the way that you'd expect a military guy would do.
Now, the reason why they don't make a president is they're not flexible enough.
I think Reagan would be a good president.
I don't know how flexible it is.
We'll wait and see.
Well, do you think that the military mind is inflexible, then, by Kenosha?
You're saying that they're not flexible enough to be a good politician.
No, what I mean is that you've got to evade.
To be a good politician, it's not to me you have to be a liar.
Lawyers make good politicians.
Yeah.
Because you've got to be able to take a guy you know damn good well as guilty as hell
And you go to paint that picture, and you say, well, I'm defending his rights, you know, that's for him, for a fair trial.
And you make him out as a good Samaritan, and that poor innocent woman probably raped as a prostitute, you know, and all that sort of thing.
So you try her and find her guilty.
Now, a politician does well because he can be on one side one day and one on the other.
And you can rationalize that.
You say, well, things change.
just like Fulbright said, well, I was wrong.
But the military mentality doesn't work that way.
I'm not sure there's a military mind.
I'm trying to explain the way that someone who I think is efficient, the civilian would call that a military mind.
He's more rigid in his thinking.
I hope I'm not that way.
I think I'm broad-minded.
I'm not one that
Also, it changes my mind on things.
There's no question about that.
But I'm just telling you their style of life and also the way they approach problems.
One would say, especially if somebody's never had any military training, that you seem to have a military mind.
Now, when they say a military mind, what they mean is they're rigid and blind to the realities of life.
They live in an entirely different world.
Why don't they get out here to the real world where we are?
What do you think?
And I don't think Maxwell Taylor, for example, has a military mind at all.
Even though he's really everything I described, that describes Maxwell Taylor.
I don't think good pastor, who was the superintendent of the military academy,
he's another real intellectual we have in the military.
You know, he's a Ph.D., and he's a patent, probably, is what the civilians would call the military mind.
Okay.
Now, for the final topic of the interview, let's turn to what has happened at Texas A&M during the last generation.
Did you know General Oral Rudder?
I think I met him one time, but I really can't say that I knew him because he was ahead of me considerably at A&M, and I didn't meet him during the war, as I recall.
He might have been at a rally.
We had Aggie Mustard and Naples during the war.
He might have been there at that time.
We got shelled.
I was wondering, during that time, of course, there were a number of very important changes.
In the school?
In the school at A&M, and one was ending the mandatory corps and allowing people to come who do not want to join the corps of cadets.
What's your feeling on that?
I thought that was a good policy.
Why?
Well, because you can't maintain a big school like that and have it
strictly military.

Certainly, if he hadn't done it when Vietnam came along and ROTC got so unpopular, I think it probably was good for the school, mainly because I thought females were good and you don't want them unless they want to take ROTC.
Okay, what did you think about his decision to allow women to come to A&M?
I thought that was good also.
See, it's an isolated place, of course, if you don't think you live there.
We used to hitchhike to Denton.
Mimi attended TSCW.
They called it CIA there, Denton, Texas.
All female schools, so we sort of adopted each other, you know.
They supported us going to football games in Dallas and also at Fort Worth.
And we used to hitchhike from College Station on weekends.
to Dentman by, can you imagine that?
Get up there on Saturday and come back on Sunday.
But I think that was a good thing because it's just healthy and good for female companionship in the classroom.
But I would certainly like to see a strong cadet corps and maintain the same standards, which I think they have,
eliminate that city hazing, although, I mean, you know, to be more mature, certainly we're more mature now than we were 15 and 20 and 30 years ago, to say May, because of the changes with May.
But that's important, because A&M has a national reputation.
You can go anywhere, and they say, you're from A&M, and you have some old time, and you say, and this isn't just a cliche, but it seems to be.
A&M produced more also in World War II than even West Point.
And we're proud of that.
And our nation was proud because that was important.
We had OCS, but here we had somebody that had been trained and was part of the training.
And they all did an outstanding job, far as I know.
And it's good for them to carry on that tradition.
And I hope that there is friction between the Corps cadets and the non-military.
See, after World War II, we had a lot of veterans.
And they made real fine students.
Of course, they were mature and married.
Most of them, boy, they were ready to get on with their life.
I would like to see us a strong Corps.
with all of the traditions, Leslie, hazing.
What about allowing the decision to integrate the school and allow blinds into Texas A&M?
What was your opinion of that?
Oh, great.
But I was in hope that maybe we would phase out Prairie View when that occurred, but I can see now where that's not going to be possible.
Either you've got to really support it or phase it out.
By support, I mean adequate buildings.
But if they breach the capacity, like we say now, they probably will need Prairie View as an overflow, certainly for the black.
Because they raise the interest standard and so forth.
You're going to eliminate some people that normally would be coming in.
And as a corollary, I was wondering what you thought about the draft.
What's your opinion, which this doesn't have to do with A&M, but what's your opinion as far as reinstituting the draft in the United States?
Of course, I think it should be reinstituted, but I don't think now is the time, mainly because of the mood of the country.
Now, if Reagan can continue to be popular or have the respect and the support of the nation and Congress, then perhaps he can do it.
But now, I'm saying, after this forgiving of the draft dodgers and that other, I think you'll have turmoil, but certainly we should consider continuing registration.
You've heard this so much over and over.
It's not the active duty forces that need to draft.
It's the reserve.
You've got to build up a train, a reservoir of trained people as individual replacement.
And we don't have it.
That's what the draft produces.
Because you know you're drafted, you do your active duty training, then you're carried for four years, I guess, or five years as a

inactive reserve and you're subject to call and we have exercises used to practicing it's good easy to do that with computers calling up providing they keep their their residents up to date in the computer practice calling them in calling them up and you say but without the draft i don't know how we're ever going to have an adequate reserve and that's that's because
We've got to be able to replace casuals in Europe.
And they're going to be heavy.
And I don't know how we're going to do it.
I don't know how in the world.
What about drafting women?
What's your opinion toward that?
We get all the females we want without the draft.
Why draft people you don't need?
Well, you say, well, why don't you put it on the books and not use it?
Maybe something like that.
in the case of all that war, would we want to, but I don't know.
What about your idea of women in combat roles?
No.
Why not?
It's just, it's too dirty and suffering, and we, this would be a hell of a nation, and we're reaching that point with this unisex approach to life.
If we have to rely on our female population to go out, I just can't see them in the,
And war is such a dirty, terrible thing.
Women ministrate that they need to bathe.
They could never have fought in Italy then.
And I wouldn't want them to, aside now from the sex part of it.
You know, that's one of the big problems now.
The gals get pregnant.
And they have children.
And they marry soldiers.
In Europe right now, one of our big problems is if we really alerted and moved out, what will they do with all those children?
The wife can't go because who's going to take care of the kids?
Well, you say, well, she has to because she's a key man in our communication unit.
So we're kidding ourselves if we think we can move out on a total alert and go somewhere in Europe and not have all sorts of problems of manning.
Plus the women get pregnant.
As I just said, they can't lift heavy objects after a while.
Some of the women are small and can't lift it anyway.
So you have to have a man come along to supplement or to do the job.
So where are you going to use them?
In combat, you've got to carry heavy loads, even throw you an instrument.
And your feet hurt.
I just don't see any place.
They're not needed anyways.
So why would we draft and use women?
We've got too many right now.
See, support units have to fight also.
Peace time, it's all simple because the other man comes and helps them.
But in peace time, it's wet, you're muddy, you're sick, you're scared.
And you're going to find men, unless we change and all get to be homosexuals, which looks like we're going to be lesbians and homosexuals or bisexuals sooner or later.
There's still a difference in the man and the woman, and that difference is not needed on the battlefield.
I don't even agree with a gal being a fighter pilot.
It's true she can go fight and hopefully she comes back and lands.
But I'd hate to see her go to prison.
What would they do like they did in Vietnam for eight and ten years?
Of course, they'll use them for sex.
They'd do it practically every war they ever had, just like we talked about there.
The German Jews, the Jewish women, the good-looking, they all kept them out for sex.
Now, overall, do you think that the changes back to A&M now, do you think that the changes during those 1960s, do you think that that made A&M a better institution or not?
I think so.
that certainly made them like all other institutions.
It's no longer unique.
We used to be proud of being really the largest military installation in the United States.
Or in some cases, the world, I've said.
Maybe that's our own propaganda.
And it was really fine school.
Of course, the school was much better now than it was then.
And we had a lot of instructors.
They had no more than a master's degree, for example.
And as I read my alumni magazines, we really got some top-notch people like you, for example, that have come from other states and not have just a bunch of texts.
And that's inbreeding.
And that's one reason we don't speak very good English is because of our teachers in high school later on.
They spoke funny just like we did.
And they're supposed to be teaching them.
Like when Mimi went on up to Denton, she had a real good speech teacher.
And she took that as an elective.
But the teacher was shocked.
Where in the world did you girls go to school?
So that's good to have.
Jefferson came from your country.
He was a dean, as we talked about earlier.
And he was good for anything.
And he was one of the pioneers, along with Dean Kyle.
Of course, he was a local product.
So we don't want inbreeding at all.
We want outside.
It's a much better school academically.
And I'd rather trade off this military value for academic excellence than be hard-headed and say, well, even though they're not going to be professional soldiers,
make everybody take ROTC.
Now, I'm not in favor of females being in the band just because the band doesn't have a female.
That's the national reputation of that band, just perfection.
They even look better on TV as a dozen persons, if you see that.
It's beautiful.
And why have a female in there just because she wasn't supposed to be?
I don't know.
What was the result of that lawsuit?
We're still in court.
Of course, it won't ruin the band.
It won't be the end of the world if that's the case.
But I hope they all are generally the size of the mail so we don't end up having a bunch of little.
I'm out of questions.
And we've covered your early life and your education and career.
And I was wondering your ideas about leadership in A&M.
I was wondering if there was anything else that
Do you think that we should, anything else that was important in your career, that we should talk about, or have we done, sort of covered the water part?
I don't think we've talked too much about everything.
Okay, well.
Does that gal, when she types it up, does she edit it, get all the grammatical errors out of it?
Oh, I'll end the interview.
